  footnotes: []
english:
  title: Record of the Gentleman's Pavilion
  author: Jung Do-jeon
  language: eng
  text: 'Among our circle there is a man of high station, whose bearing stands noble and refined, whose integrity stands elevated and singular—a true gentleman. One day he built a new pavilion beneath the pines and invited us to gather there over wine, asking me to name it. I pointed to the pines and spoke thus: "See how their verdant needles drape like noble whiskers, how their bent forms mirror the graceful posture of virtue. In the depths of winter, when wind scours and snow lashes, when all green things break and wither, these pines stand solitary, their loss of leaves delayed. In the height of summer, when stones melt and metal flows, when all creatures fade and sicken, these remain verdant and unchanging. This is the steadfast heart of the gentleman—unmoved by poverty, unbent by force. Shall we not call this pavilion the Gentleman''s Pavilion?"'
  footnotes:
  - key: ''
    value: 'The poem alludes to the classical tradition of learned men choosing plants that reflect their character: Qu Yuan (靈均), the passionate poet, favored orchids for their purity; Tao Yuanming (靖節), the recluse, favored chrysanthemums for their solitary grace.'
  - key: ''
    value: Jung Do-jeon uses the pine tree as a moral exemplar—its constancy through seasons mirrors the gentleman's unwavering virtue regardless of circumstance.
  - key: ''
    value: The pavilion becomes not merely a place of gathering, but a testament to shared values among those of cultivated spirit who resist the corruption of their times.
